Technical Forensic Markers and Network Identification
The technical identifiers present on the card provide a definitive map of its origin and capabilities. These markers, such as the ICA number and manufacturing codes, are used by the Mastercard network to ensure that every transaction is routed to the correct clearinghouse and that the risk associated with each transaction is properly managed.
Analysis of ICA-4473 and the Mastercard Network
The Interbank Card Association (ICA) number is a four-to-six-digit identifier assigned by Mastercard to uniquely identify the member institution responsible for a card’s activity. ICA-4473 is a specific identifier linked to Pathward, N.A.. This number is essential for the settlement process; when a consumer swipes a JaffPay card at a merchant terminal, the terminal uses the ICA to determine which bank must ultimately authorize the transaction and provide the funds.
The ICA is more than a routing number; it is a marker of institutional responsibility. Every transaction conducted under ICA-4473 is the legal responsibility of Pathward, meaning Pathward must ensure that the transaction complies with Anti-Money Laundering (AML) laws and that the cardholder has sufficient funds on deposit. The association of ICA-4473 with the JaffPay card confirms that despite the JaffSpace branding, the financial liability and regulatory reporting remain with Pathward.
